General FAQ

This document is a community driven full breakdown of the respective class. This is a live document where we actively change it based on feedback and changes to the game to provide the best information to the community. The majority of us hang around in the Community Lost Ark Discord in our respective class channels. If you would like to give us feedback or ask questions contact us there.

About Aeromancer

Aeromancer possesses two distinct sets of skills: Umbrella skills and Weather skills. Depending on your chosen engraving, your skillset will vary accordingly. As a solid and consistent DPS class with good burst potential, Aeromancer offers two strong engravings, each with its own unique playstyle that is easy to grasp.

Aeromancer's gimmick revolves around Sun Shower, and both engravings incorporate this aspect. In the following section, we will delve further into this mechanic.

About Sun Shower


Upon fully filling the Raindrop gauge, activating Sun Shower enhances your normal attack and movement skill. Additionally, an AoE is created around Aeromancer inflicting continuous tick damage to enemies within it and have their attack power reduced by 10%. This skill lasts for 12 seconds.

Equipping the Wind Fury engraving increases Raindrop gauge consumption by 50%. Sun Shower is now an Umbrella skill, the duration is now 8 seconds and the AoE is reduced. Sun Shower no longer inflicts 10% attack power reduction debuff on foes but instead grants a 12% attack and movement speed buff to allies within the AoE. Moreover, using an Umbrella skill within 3 seconds of another Umbrella skill restores 12% of the raindrop gauge.

With the Drizzle engraving equipped, Raindrop gauge consumption is reduced by 50%, extending Sun Shower duration to 24 seconds. Additionally, Sun Shower increases Weather skill damage by 7/15/30% when in use.

Although not recommended, using both engravings will cancel out the gauge consumption buff/debuff, decrease Sun Shower's AoE, and increase Weather damage by 7/15/30%. Furthermore, Sun Shower will no longer inflict 10% attack power reduction debuff on foes but will provide a 12% attack and movement speed buff to allies within  the AoE.

Base Sun Shower is considered a Weather skill and benefits from all damage boosts provided to Weather skills. This includes Weather damage increase from Drizzle and the spec stat. However, when you equip the Wind Fury engraving it becomes an Umbrella skill and will no longer benefit from the spec stat.

Party Synergy

 A synergy is a buff/debuff provided by a player that increases the entire party’s potential in combat. This is pretty essential in PvE activities for Lost Ark and should always be taken in consideration when planning team compositions for high-end content.

Spec Scaling

Spec increases her Weather skills damage, increases Sun Shower gauge gain, and increases awakening damage.
Spec DOES NOT increase Umbrella skills damage.

1 Spec =
0.07% Weather skills damage increase

0.035% Sun Shower gauge gain

0.0535% Awakening damage increase

Perception of Aeromancer

Aeromancer brings a lot to the table synergy wise. She is well sought after in all parties that’s not looking for a Deathblade + Gunlancer combo for positional synergy. She provides synergies that everyone wants while also bringing decent damage to the team. She can also be treated like an offensive support. She is the Deathblade/Gunlancer to hit master classes. Just like Deathblade, she is also a King maker.

How well does Aeromancer perform?

Aeromancer is a very simple class to play, which naturally translates to a high damage floor. A perk for being a Hit Master class is that they perform very well in the later stages of the game, especially in prog/late-game content. However, it's worth noting that her DPS ceiling is lower compared to other classes, this is apparent in high-skill level content(e.g. Inferno/Hell), which creates a noticeable disparity. Nonetheless, this doesn't imply that she's ineffective in high-skill level content, as she's still very capable of pulling her own weight.

Wind Fury vs Drizzle

It depends on many variables: your team composition and gear, specific encounter and clear time, among others. In theory, Drizzle and Wind Fury do the same damage, they just have different damage profiles: Drizzle has a bursty damage profile, whereas Wind Fury is constant damage.

On any overgeared homework content (i.e Clown G3), Drizzle is more likely to come out on top because the shorter the encounter, the more damage you'll have contributed as Drizzle since you're bursting from mech to mech.

On hell mode and long fights (i.e Brel G4), Wind Fury is more likely to come out on top because it can just keep going and has more opportunities to get back into doing damage fast, while Drizzle having to deal with mechs or DPS cuts might really hurt its damage profile and identity generation, just like Igniter Sorc.

Any of the two specs can absolutely outdamage the other though, in accordance with how good each player is. Don't pick a spec based on which one does more damage in theory, but rather based on your affinity with the spec fantasy, aesthetics, stats preference, etc... Absolute god tier play should make both extremely close to each other damage wise.

Why is Yearning important?

It’s considered a part of a build despite not being on your character.

Yearning is used by supports and gives +8/10/12% Damage and Attack/Move speed to the party. This is a Gear Set they use that has a golden ring.

Playstyle

Wind Fury Aeromancer's gameplay revolves around rapid skill spamming. Mana reliance is heavy due to the nature of swift-based classes. The main mechanic is Current. Current is a shield that lasts for 3 seconds, it is obtained from skills with Current Occurrence. This shield is consumed by skills with Reversal for a damage increase to the skill in return. Alternate between applying and spending Current while maintaining your crit synergy for maximum damage.

Stat Allocation

Swift is the go to stat for Wind Fury, as it directly scales with swift, higher swift will increase your crit rate and crit dmg. Crit is also important and is the higher priority stat for the nightmare build.

Circulate(Very Good)

When landing an attack, for 30 seconds gain “Circulation”. For the first 10 seconds, skill damage +2.5/3/3.5/4%; for the next 10 seconds, Crit Rate +4/5/6/7%; for the last 10 seconds, Crit Damage +6/8/10/12%.

Fervor(Very Good)

When landing an attack while your HP is above 40%, gain “Fervor” for 3s, which increases Damage dealt by 2.5/3/3.5/4%. The effect of Passion is increased by 1% if you have 'Cool-Headed'.

Precise(Good)

When landing an attack, increase Crit Rate by 2/3/4/5%.

Superiority(Good)

When landing an attack, increase Damage by 1.5/2/2.5/3%.

Hammer(Alright)

When landing an attack, gain “Hammer” for 8s, which gives a +6/8/10/12% Crit Damage buff. The effect of Hammer is increased by an additional 8% if you have 'Steel Wedge'.

Assail(Alright)

When landing an attack, increase Crit Damage by 4/6/8/10%.

Wedge(OK)

On a successful hit. Gain a Wedge effect for 8 seconds. At 4 stacks of Wedge, gain Steel Wedge for 8s, doubling the Additional Damage Increase. Wedge: On Successful hit, Additional Damage +0.3/0.35/0.45/0.5%

Mp Recovery(Nice to have)

20% chance to recover 125/150/175/200 MP when using a skill that consumes MP.

Max MP +150/200/250/300

FAQ: Wind Fury

Questions sourced from frequent interactions within the Unofficial Lost Ark Discord #Aeromancer
This section is ever-growing, and new FAQ submissions are always welcome.

Hallucination vs Nightmare vs Dominion

Hallucination is the default and most popular set due to its high crit rate, which provides consistent damage output. It is considered the most reliable set out of the three and is recommended for most players due to its simplicity.

The Nightmare set offers significant damage, as well as cooldown reduction and mana regeneration when in the boundless state. This set excels in burst DPS but has a lower overall DPS potential. To optimize this set, you will need to adjust your stat distribution. Instead of going full swift with crit on the necklace, you should aim for a 50/50 split between swift and crit, while setting your pet to prioritize crit. With this build, mana management will be the least of your concerns, as reaching the boundless state will help regenerate your mana without significantly hindering your DPS.

The Dominion set has the highest DPS potential among the three sets, but it is also the most challenging to master. This set requires a spammy playstyle, which makes mana management crucial. You will need to equip additional Focus runes and ensure you have a competent support. Consuming mana food may also help alleviate your mana issues.

Overall, while Hallucination is the recommended set for most players due to its reliability, the Nightmare and Dominion sets offer unique advantages for those seeking burst damage or high potential, respectively. Each set requires careful consideration of stat distribution and playstyle adjustments to maximize their effectiveness.

Why is Keen Blunt Weapon inefficient for Wind Fury?

Wind Fury provides crit dmg, 36% assuming your attack speed is 140%. On top of the 36% crit dmg you get from Wind Fury, two of your main damaging skills have the Thunderbolt tripod. This tripod adds an additional 140%-210% crit dmg to Piercing Wind and 95-180% crit dmg to Rage.

What's the best stat distribution?

All of them are very close, and are mostly up to preference. The more swift, the more pressure to get skills on cooldown to maintain DPS, and the more mana issues you might run into from spamming. The full swift Hallucination build holds a lot of damage consistency over 50/50 Nightmare though. Generally, you get less overall crit chance in Nightmare, and boundless state ping pong makes it less consistent damage wise, but you're mana issue free.

In Hallucination, if you play 5x3+1 with Adrenaline as your +1, it’s highly recommended to use a crit earring. If Adrenaline is your +2, or by the time elixirs arrive in the West, a crit ring is suitable. You can also swap that crit accessory for a swift one if your party has an extra crit synergy.

That being said, the higher ceiling build is Dominion because of the extra cooldown reduction it provides, but only by a tiny margin, and it requires a lot more DPS uptime to be on par with other options. The more crit you get away with, the higher its ceiling, but you need to prioritize your Awakening’s cooldown over anything else.

As you can see, Wind Fury has tons of options that are all very much viable and up to preference, party compatibility, and comfort. If you have the opportunity, testing different variants in Trixion before committing to a specific one is highly recommended.

How can I deal with mana?

Wind Fury has tons of build variants that have different ways of dealing with mana. The default build in this guide is the one that makes mana the easiest to handle. It’s not the ceiling damage build.

Removing some Galewind runes for Focus runes is a good first option to reduce mana consumption.

Mana food is a good way to combat the mana issues, albeit an expensive (or time consuming) one over a long time.

For comfort content like Guardian Raids, some people will go for a MP recovery bracelet with one stat, but we do advise against "chasing" MP Recovery on a swift/crit bracelet. It is simply not worth paying a ton of pheons and gold over.

You can also trade the damage stability of Hallucination for a one stop mana solving set like Nightmare and just not worry about mana at all, but unless you have very high uptime, your damage will perform worse damage-wise on average.

What level CDR gems do I need to have a comfy rotation?

Generally speaking, there is no breakpoint with CDR gems on Wind Fury. If you are serious about your character though, you'll want to try to run full 7s, and eventually aim for having 4 lvl 9s for your 4 main spenders.

The reason is very simple, whenever executing your damage rotation, you'll quickly notice that the bottleneck will be Piercing Wind (and your other spenders) coming off-cooldown a tiny bit after you finish your rotation (2-4s). The lower you bring that down, the lower downtime you're gonna face when playing. However it is not always realistic to try to have 0 downtime, bosses move and do mechs, which is why it isn't a major requirement.

You can test this in Trixion and see where your own comfort zone falls, but from our testing, lvl 9s are the sweet spot you want to aim for. The more the better.

Whirlpool VS Wiping Wind?

Both skills are very valid options. Your pick must depend on what you’re chasing: highest damage ceiling would go to Wiping Wind, whereas the least mana intensive build would be Whirlpool. The damage difference is about 2%, which can be recouped with the use of Quick Recharge instead of Focus runes.

Different encounters and party compositions may also force you into choosing one over the other for higher stagger or weak point checks.

Playstyle

Drizzle Aeromancer's main objective is building meter and unleashing skills during their identity window. Cast high damaging skills within Sun Shower as Drizzle amplifies Weather skills damage. Use skills from highest damaging to least damaging within the identity window. Skillful meter management maximizes Drizzle Aeromancer's effectiveness.

Stat Allocation

Drizzle is spec based, it is needed to generate meter and increase your Weather damage. Crit is your secondary stat that will be on your necklace and bracelet.

FAQ: Drizzle

Questions sourced from frequent interactions within the Unofficial Lost Ark Discord #Aeromancer
This section is ever-growing, and new FAQ submissions are always welcome.

What does 6:2, 5:3, and 4:4 mean?

The numbers represent the amount of Weather and Umbrella skills you’re running, 6:2 means your build consists of 6 Weather skills and 2 Umbrella skills

What’s the big difference between 6:2, 5:3 and 4:4?

6:2 is the standard build that produces the most consistent damage output, because Drizzle only impacts Weather skills.

5:3 is an attempt at solving an underlying issue of Drizzle: low weak points. You use piercing wind for its 2 weak points damage and the decent damage it deals, but your Drizzle engraving doesn't boost it at all.

4:4 is a very niche build nowadays. Although it is a viable build, it usually does not perform as well as the recommended 6:2 or 5:3 variants due to being much more clunkier to pull off. Piercing Wind and Wind Gimlet both are slow with very long cooldown. If missed, the dps will drop much more than if missing a skill on the other builds.. Adrenaline is also more difficult to maintain with those longer cd. If you manage to pull it off however, it can perform just as well as 6:2 and 5:3.

It is recommended for people to test this build alongside other variants fully before committing to it. 4:4 Should be picked solely for the gameplay experience.

Why is Conviction and Judgment taken?

Conviction Judgment is taken for the cooldown reduction to better align your Rainstorm+Strong Wind and Scorching Sun+Wiping Wind combo. The idea behind this is you proc conviction judgment with Tornado+Whirlpool for Scorching Sun and Wiping Wind, doing this will reduce their cooldown and let you cast them earlier within Sun Shower the second time. This is because you want Scorching Sun+Wiping Wind to be up by the time you fill up and use Sun Shower again.

What level gems do I need to fit two Scorching Suns into a Sun Shower window?

Level 5 gems are enough but higher level gems will make it more comfy.

What are the spec breakpoints for Drizzle?

The spec needed to fill up your identity on Drizzle is relatively low. Even with level 4 identity generation tripods and double purple wealth runes, you can easily fill up identity using the abilities Rainstorm, Strong Wind, and Whirlpool. In short, you do not need to be concerned about how much spec you have to charge your identity gauge (Assuming you go full spec).

How mobile is Drizzle?

Drizzle being a spec build makes it have a low default move speed. However, there are a few tools to help with that:

Spread's 2nd line tripod gives you 20% move speed for 4 seconds, which is a comfy burst of speed pretty often. If you do take it.

During identity, her space bar becomes a combo which lets you dodge and reposition a lot easier.

Strong wind does have a move speed tripod, but you're giving up cooldown reduction for it, which makes it harder to charge your identity. It's an option though not recommended.

Can I run Adrenaline 1 on Drizzle?

Drizzle is generally crit starved, so while going Adrenaline 1 and Cursed Doll 3 is a possibility and a higher damage ceiling in most cases, it can feel bad to play because of white numbers, especially if your character isn’t fully decked out.

Going Adrenaline 1 starts being more of a serious optimization if you get a really good crit chance bracelet (Precise effect for example). When we get Elixirs, the crit chance elixir set will also provide a comfy 7% crit chance overall, which makes it easier to run that kind of setup.
